This study explores the global average pooling layer's role in convolutional neural networks, revealing its explicit capability to enhance localization even when trained solely on image-level labels. Initially proposed for training regularization, the layer proves to create a versatile deep representation applicable to diverse tasks. Despite the simplicity of global average pooling, the approach achieves a 37.1% top-5 error for object localization on ILSVRC 2014, closely approaching the performance of a fully supervised CNN with a 34.2% top-5 error.}